Cnemaspis adangrawi

sp. nov. is known only from Adang and Rawi islands, 60 and 61 km off the coast of Thailand, respectively (
Fig. 1
). All Adang specimens were found in a granitic rocky stream (
Fig. 13A
). Rawi Island specimens were found in rock outcrops along a stream (
Fig. 13B
) and along a forest stream near mangroves (
Fig. 13C
). Sixteen specimens (ZMKU R 00767-00768, ZMKU R 00770-00772, ZMKU R 00775-00776, THNHM 28206-28209, and THNHM 28211-28215) were collected during the day (1047-1823 h) and four specimens (ZMKU R 00769, ZMKU R 00773-00774, and THNHM 28210) were collected at night (1927-2024 h). The male holotype was found during the day (1047 
h
) on the base of a rock boulder with holes formed by the expansive soil between the ground and rock interface of a nearby stream.
